<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">As competition in retail intensifies, technology has become one of the clearest levers executives have for improving the customer experience without simply adding headcount or floor space. To understand how that plays out in practice, Teamwork Commerce and Retail Dive surveyed more than 100 retail executives in August 2023 on their mobile point-of-sale strategy — what they've already invested in, and what's still on the roadmap.</p>

<h2>Why mobile POS became a strategic question, not just an IT one</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Mobile POS started as a convenience feature — a way to take a line-buster device out during a rush. For the executives surveyed, it has since become something closer to a strategic bet: untethering associates from a fixed register changes how a store operates, from clienteling on the floor to fulfilling online orders from the back room. The survey set out to measure how far that shift had actually progressed, rather than how far vendors claim it has.</p>

<h2>What the data reveals about the gap</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The report's purpose was to give retail leaders a way to benchmark themselves: is your mobile POS deployment ahead of the pack, keeping pace, or lagging behind peers who are already using it for more than basic transactions? The exercise is less about a single number and more about self-assessment — the survey gives retailers language for questions like whether their current mobile POS investment matches the customer experience they're actually trying to deliver.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">That distinction matters because "having mobile POS" and "using mobile POS well" are different maturity stages. A tablet at the front of the store that only handles overflow lines is a very different deployment than associates carrying a full-featured POS everywhere on the floor — able to check inventory across the enterprise, process a return, or ship a size that isn't in stock, all from the same device a customer is standing in front of.</p>

<h2>Where the leaders are actually pulling ahead</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The retailers furthest along tend to share a pattern: mobile POS isn't a bolt-on running alongside their main system, it is the main system. Associates using an iPhone or iPad as a full-featured POS can sell from the fitting room, the stockroom, or the sales floor rather than walking a customer back to a register. When that device also carries enterprise-wide inventory visibility, a stockout on the shelf stops being a lost sale — an associate can locate the item at another store or a warehouse and ship it in a few taps, which is a meaningful part of why some footwear brands report double-digit revenue lift from that single capability.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The retailers further behind are usually not behind on hardware. They're behind on integration — mobile devices that can ring a sale but can't see live inventory, can't process the same promotions and loyalty logic as the main register, or can't hand off an order to fulfillment without a phone call to the back room.</p>

<h2>The gap that's left to close</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">For most retailers, the work ahead isn't buying more devices. It's closing the distance between what the mobile device is capable of and how much of the store's operation actually runs through it. The survey's core message, distilled, is that mobile POS adoption is broad but uneven — the technology has arrived in most stores, but the depth of what it's used for still varies enormously, and that variance is exactly where competitive separation is happening.</p>
